In JS Strings are immutable


it is a sequence of characters : "Shashank" 	<-- this is a string

let str="javascript";

few string inbuilt functions:
1> length : to find the length of the string.

let str="shashank";
console.log(str.length);	// output : 8

2> access through index.

let str="shashank";
console.log(str[0],str[7]);


Few More String Meathods in JS.

1> .toUpperCase() : to convert string in uppercase.	// SHASHANK
let str='shashank';

2> .toLowerCase() : to convert string in lowercase.	// CHAUHAN
let str='CHAUHAN';

3> .trim() : remove the useless whitespaces.
let str='       Hello World     ';	// 'Hello World'
console.log(str.trim());
3.1> .trimLeft();	// 'Hello World	' 
3.2> .trimRight();	// '	Hello World'

4> .slice(start,end) : to extract a part from the string.
let str='hello world';
console.log(str.slice(2,9));

5> .concat() : use to concat two strings.
let str1='hello ';
let str2='world';
let concatedStr=str1.concat(str2);
console.log(concatedStr);

we can also use + to concatinate two strings.

let str1='hello ';
let str2='world';
let concatedStr=str1+str2+123;		
console.log(concatedStr);		// hello world123

"name"+124	// output is name124
123+"hlo"		// output is 123hlo
